Fertility & Development - How do education and infrastructure affect fertility?

1) Introduction

In the following, the fertil2 dataset from the wooldridge package is used to test assumptions of development economics. Precisely, it will be observed how different socioeconomic factors influence fertility. Eventually, an ML model will be trained to predict ever born children (= fertility) based on a set of independent variables.

4) Random seed and train-test split in 80-20 ratio

set.seed(123)
train_index <- createDataPartition(df$ceb, p = 0.8, list = F)
train_data <- df[train_index, ]
test_data <- df[-train_index, ]

## evermarr  0.000000    0.07262164    TRUE  TRUE
formula <- ceb ~ urban*educ + poly(age, 2) + urban*electric + agefbrth + agefm + educ*heduc + spirit + protest + catholic

ctrl <- trainControl(
  method = "repeatedcv",
  number = 10,
  repeats = 3
)

grid <- expand.grid(
  alpha  = seq(0, 1, length.out = 11),
  lambda = 10 ^ seq(-3, 1, length.out = 30)
)

rf_grid <- expand.grid(
  mtry = c(2,4,6,8,10)
)

# First model
dev_model_glmnet <- train(
  formula,
  data = train_data,
  method = "glmnet",
  trControl = ctrl,
  preProcess = c("center", "scale", "medianImpute"),
  tuneGrid = grid,
  metric = "RMSE"
)
## Warning in nominalTrainWorkflow(x = x, y = y, wts = weights, info = trainInfo,
## : There were missing values in resampled performance measures.
# Second model
dev_model_poisson <- train(
  formula,
  data = train_data,
  method = "glm",
  family = "poisson",
  trControl = ctrl
)
prediction <- predict(dev_model_glmnet, newdata = test_data)
pred_poisson <- predict(dev_model_poisson, newdata = test_data)

results <- data.frame(
  Actual = test_data$ceb,
  Predicted = prediction,
  Predicted_Poisson = pred_poisson
)

rmse <- sqrt(mean((results$Actual - results$Predicted)^2))
rmse_poisson <- sqrt(mean((results$Actual - results$Predicted_Poisson)^2))
print(paste("RMSE: ", rmse))

It is the textbook assumption of development economics, that as female education increases fertility rates drop. The graphic and accompanying linear regression confirm that assumption.

7) Fertility in Urban vs.Rural Areas

ggplot(df, aes(x = factor(urban), y = ceb)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(
    title = "Fertility in Urban vs. Rural Areas",
    x = "Urban (1 = Yes, 0 = No)",
    y = "Number of Children"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

t.test(ceb ~ urban, data = df)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  ceb by urban
## t = 9.7697, df = 1582.1, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group 0 and group 1 is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.8598821 1.2918944
## sample estimates:
## mean in group 0 mean in group 1 
##        4.489308        3.413420

It is another textbook assumption that females in urban areas tend to have fewer children than those in rural areas. The graphic above and the accompanying t-test confirm that assumption and show that in fact, females in urban areas usually (95% confidence) have between 0.86 to 1.29 children less than those in rural areas.

9) Comparison to baseline assumption

print(paste("RMSE: ", rmse))
## [1] "RMSE:  1.5801192103796"
print(paste("RMSE_Poisson: ", rmse_poisson))
## [1] "RMSE_Poisson:  1.56268736581785"
print(paste("SD(ceb): ", sd(df$ceb)))
## [1] "SD(ceb):  2.31452645520565"

The Poisson models RMSE equals 1.56, i.e.on average the model is off by 1.56 ever born children. Given the complex social, cultural and economic factors that influence fertility, the model has a moderate level of predictive accuracy, but also highlights important unexplained variation. The standard deviation of the dependent variable (ceb) is 2.31. This indicates that the model performs better than a naive baseline prediction that just guesses the mean number of ever born children for all observations.
